name: Causal Search with LLM
description: Run Causal Search methods with an LLM to enhance (if provided) a causal graph (as a DAG) and return a SEM description.

components.name: Csv Upload
components.description:
Reads a CSV file.
Inputs:
  `Input file` (File): A File object with a field `path` (str) containing the local path to the local CSV file to read. If needed, the local path can be inputted manually by the user.
Output (File): A File object with a field `preview` which has the value pandas.read_csv(file_path, nrows=10).head().to_csv(). This means that the field contains a record formatted pandas dataframe of the data in the inputted CSV file (if we see the CSV file as a m*n matrix M, the format becomes a string `,M(1,1),M(1,2),...,M(1,n) 0,M(2,1),...,M(2,n) 1,M(3,n),... ... M(m,n)`).
components.label: CSVEXTRACTOR-0

components.name: Causal Discovery Algorithms with a LLM
components.description:
Run Causal Discovery algorithms with the help of a LLM to run different methods
    
    Inputs:
        Data Path (str): Path to the file
        Data Separator (str): Separator of the file
        Background Graph (str): Node-Link formatted Graph
        Context (str): Context for the causal discovery algorithm
        Log File Name (str): Name of the log file to store the step-by-step reasoning of the LLM and results
        
    Outputs:
        Results (JSON):
            - SEM object with the results of the causal discovery algorithm turned into a SEM description
            - Agent output

inputs.value: This data lists various diagnostic measures recorded from 750 women along with a 0/1 variable, Outcome, that indicates whether the person eventually tested positive for diabetes. The diagnostic measures are the following: Pregnancies: number of times the woman has been pregnant. Glucose: plasma glucose concentration (mg/dl) at 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT). Blood Pressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg). Skin Thickness: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm). Insulin: insulin concentration (\u00b5 U/ml) at 2 hours in an OGTT. BMI: body mass index (weight in kg)/(height in m). Diabetes Pedigree: a numerical score designed to measure the genetic influence of both the woman\u2019s diabetic and non\u2011diabetic relatives on diabetes risk: higher scores mean more close relatives with diabetes. Age: in years. Outcome: 1 if the woman eventually tested positive for diabetes, zero otherwise. I specially want to know which variables have a causal impact on the Outcome (diabetes)

value.agent: Based on the systematic causal inference results and the final DAG, the variables Glucose and BloodPressure have a direct causal impact on the Outcome variable (diabetes). This suggests that higher levels of Glucose and BloodPressure may lead to an increased likelihood of testing positive for diabetes. Other variables in the dataset do not have direct causal relationships with the Outcome variable based on the current analysis.
value.sem:
{
    "model_spec": """
        # structural part
        Glucose ~ Pregnancies + SkinThickness
        BloodPressure ~ Pregnancies + SkinThickness
        Insulin ~ SkinThickness + Age
        BMI ~ Glucose + BloodPressure + SkinThickness + DiabetesPedigree + Age
        Outcome ~ Glucose + BloodPressure + Insulin + Age
        
        # measurement model
        
        # residual correlations
        
    """,
    "latent_descriptions": {
        "eta1": "Latent variable representing overall health indicators",
        "eta2": "Latent variable representing insulin sensitivity",
        "eta3": "Latent variable representing metabolic health"
    }
}

components.name: Property Getter
components.description:
Extracts the mapped value of an inputted key/field/attribute in an inputted object/datastructure. It can be the value of a field/attribute in an object, or the mapped value of a key in a dictionary.
    Input (Any, str): An object and a string with the name of the key/field/attribute to extract the value from. The object can for example be a Dict or a File object. If needed, the key/field/attribute can be inputted manually by the user. If nested objects/dicts, access nested keys by concatenating keys with dots (eg. `parent_dict_key.dict_key`).
    Output (Any): The mapped value of the inputted key/field/attribute in the inputted dictionary.

components.name: Background Graph reader

    Inputs:

    Output (Any): The value of the variable `result` in the Python code after execution.
